# Null Safety
- **Never** use `!!`. Use `?.`, `?:`, `requireNotNull(x) { "msg" }`, or `checkNotNull`.
- Prefer non-nullable types in signatures; push nulls to the boundary.

```kotlin
// BAD
val name = user!!.profile!!.displayName

// GOOD
val name = user?.profile?.displayName ?: "Anonymous"
```

# Exception Handling
- **Never** swallow exceptions. Empty `catch {}` and `runCatching{...}.getOrNull()` to mask failures are forbidden unless explicitly requested.
- Catch the **narrowest** type you can handle; rethrow or wrap the rest.
- Log with context, then react.

```kotlin
// BAD
try { repo.save(item) } catch (_: Exception) {}

// GOOD
try {
    repo.save(item)
} catch (e: IOException) {
    Log.e(TAG, "save failed for id=${item.id}", e)
    throw PersistenceError("save failed", e)
}
```

# Exhaustive `when`
- For sealed classes/interfaces and enums, **omit `else`** so the compiler enforces updates when new subtypes appear. Use `when` as an expression to force exhaustiveness.

```kotlin
sealed interface UiState { object Loading : UiState; data class Ready(val data: String) : UiState; data class Error(val msg: String) : UiState }

val text: String = when (state) {
    UiState.Loading -> "..."
    is UiState.Ready -> state.data
    is UiState.Error -> state.msg
}
```

# Compiler Compliance
- Treat all warnings as errors. Assume `allWarningsAsErrors` and `-Xjsr305=strict`.
- Resolve every deprecation; never `@Suppress` without a justification comment.
- For Java interop, annotate platform types explicitly (`@JvmField`, `@JvmStatic`, `@Nullable`/`@NonNull` on Java sources you touch).
